CAAA Implementation Proposal: COSMIC Accessible Agent Applet
1. Executive Summary
This proposal details the engineering blueprint for the COSMIC Accessible Agent Applet (CAAA), a native desktop accessibility tool designed for air-gapped, high-security environments running Pop!_OS. CAAA integrates a headless reasoning core (caaa-core) with a native libcosmic system tray applet, providing real-time cognitive assistance, Obsidian vault management, and constitutional AI governance without external network dependency. The architecture enforces a strict "Single Source of Truth" model where the STATUS_BLOCK is computed deterministically from ground-truth state by an isolated audit thread, preventing LLM hallucination in critical UI elements. The system utilizes mTLS-secured gRPC for inter-process communication, local Ollama instances for multi-tier LLM inference, and embedded Prolog/Lisp engines for symbolic reasoning. This document resolves six critical defects in SRS v1.2, defines a milestone-driven implementation roadmap, and establishes rigorous testing and deployment protocols for immediate engineering execution.
2. Granular Three-Phase Roadmap
The implementation is structured into three logical phases comprising nine distinct milestones (M0-M8). Progression is gated by technical verification, not calendar time.
Phase 0: Foundation & Security (Milestones M0-M2)
M0: Secure Scaffold & PKI Provisioning
- Establish Cargo workspace with 11 crates (caaa-core, caaa-applet, caaa-proto, caaa-vault, caaa-audit, caaa-reasoning, caaa-llm, caaa-config, caaa-cli, caaa-test-utils, caaa-bin).
- Implement self-signed PKI generation utility (root CA, server cert, client cert) with hard-coded validity periods suitable for air-gap.
- Configure mTLS handshake logic in caaa-proto; verify bidirectional certificate validation.
- Deliverable: caaa-pki-init binary and successful mTLS handshake test between dummy client/server.
M1: Core Daemon & State Schema
- Implement caaa-core state machine with atomic ground-truth storage (JSON/SQLite).
- Develop the Isolated Audit Thread with exclusive file handles for write-only operations.
- Define protobuf schemas for StateSnapshot, UserIntent, and ConstitutionalVerdict.
- Deliverable: Headless daemon accepting gRPC connections, persisting state, and rejecting non-mTLS clients.
M2: Reasoning Engine Integration
- Integrate Ollama API wrapper within caaa-llm supporting model hot-swapping (TinyLlama -> Mistral -> Llama3).
- Embed SWI-Prolog and Tiny Lisp interpreters in caaa-reasoning for symbolic constraint checking.
- Implement the "Constitutional Layer" middleware that intercepts LLM outputs for Prolog-based rule validation.
- Deliverable: Core capable of processing a prompt through LLM -> Constitutional Filter -> Final Response.
Phase 1: Logic & Interface (Milestones M3-M6)
M3: Obsidian Vault Subsystem
- Implement caaa-vault with atomic write operations to Markdown files.
- Develop graph traversal logic for linking notes based on semantic similarity.
- Enforce "Audit-Only Write" policy: all vault modifications must pass through the audit thread.
- Deliverable: Verified creation/modification of Obsidian notes via gRPC calls.
M4: STATUS_BLOCK Deterministic Computation
- Develop the deterministic algorithm for computing STATUS_BLOCK (System Load, Active Model, Vault Integrity, Constitutional Status) strictly from ground-truth state.
- Explicitly ban LLM involvement in status generation.
- Expose GetStatus() gRPC method returning the computed block.
- Deliverable: Unit tests proving STATUS_BLOCK consistency regardless of LLM output.
M5: Libcosmic Applet Scaffold
- Initialize caaa-applet using libcosmic applet template.
- Implement system tray icon with dynamic status indicator (color-coded based on STATUS_BLOCK).
- Build the basic popup window structure with accessibility-ready layout (high contrast, screen reader labels).
- Deliverable: Running applet showing static status data.
M6: Interactive UI & Event Loop
- Connect applet UI to gRPC client stubs.
- Implement chat interface within the applet popup with streaming response support.
- Add keyboard navigation shortcuts (Super+Space trigger) and voice activation hooks.
- Deliverable: Functional chat interface capable of sending/receiving messages via the core.
Phase 2: Integration & Hardening (Milestones M7-M8)
M7: Air-Gap Bundle Integration
- Package binaries (caaa-core, caaa-applet, ollama, prolog) into the airgapped_llm bundle structure.
- Write systemd service units for caaa-core.service (headless) and caaa-applet.desktop (autostart).
- Implement startup health checks verifying mTLS certs and model availability.
- Deliverable: Single installer script deploying the full stack on fresh Pop!_OS.
M8: Final Validation & Accessibility Audit
- Execute full test matrix (see Section 6).
- Conduct manual accessibility audit with screen readers (Orca) and keyboard-only navigation.
- Perform penetration testing on the gRPC interface and vault file permissions.
- Deliverable: Release Candidate v1.0 signed and ready for deployment.
3. Technical Architecture Specifications
3.1 Component Topology
- caaa-applet (GUI): Native Rust binary using libcosmic. Runs in user session. Displays STATUS_BLOCK and chat UI. Communicates via gRPC over localhost Unix socket.
- caaa-core (Daemon): Headless Rust binary. Manages state, orchestrates LLM/Prolog, handles vault I/O. Runs as user systemd service.
- caaa-reasoning (Library): Embedded Prolog/Lisp engines for symbolic logic. Linked statically into core.
- caaa-vault (Library): Safe wrappers for Obsidian markdown manipulation. Enforces atomic writes.
- Transport: gRPC over Unix Domain Socket (/run/user/UID/caaa.sock) protected by mTLS.
3.2 gRPC Service Definition (caaa.proto)
protobuf
syntax = "proto3";
package caaa.v1;
service CAAACore {
  // Stream chat messages; server streams back tokens
  rpc ChatStream(stream ChatRequest) returns (stream ChatResponse);
  
  // Get deterministic status block (No LLM involved)
  rpc GetStatus(Empty) returns (StatusBlock);
  
  // Query Obsidian vault
  rpc SearchVault(SearchQuery) returns (VaultResults);
  
  // Execute vault write (Audited)
  rpc WriteNote(NoteEdit) returns (WriteReceipt);
  
  // System control
  rpc SwitchModel(ModelRequest) returns (ModelStatus);
}
message StatusBlock {
  string active_model = 1;
  int32 context_window_usage = 2;
  bool vault_integrity_ok = 3;
  string constitutional_mode = 4; // "STRICT", "ADVISORY", "OFF"
  uint64 uptime_seconds = 5;
  string error_state = 6; // Empty if healthy
}
message ChatRequest {
  string session_id = 1;
  string content = 2;
  optional ContextHint hint = 3;
}
message ChatResponse {
  oneof response {
    string token_delta = 1;
    string final_verdict = 2; // From Constitutional Layer
    bool stopped = 3;
  }
}

3.3 Data Flow: Chat Turn
1\. Input: User types in Applet -> ChatRequest sent via gRPC.
2\. Ingestion: Core receives request, logs to Audit Thread (write-ahead log).
3\. Context: Core retrieves relevant Obsidian notes via caaa-vault.
4\. Reasoning: 
- LLM generates draft response.
- caaa-reasoning runs Prolog constraints on draft.
- If violation detected, draft is rejected/modified based on Constitution.
5\. Output: Stream tokens back to Applet.
6\. Finalize: Audit Thread commits final exchange to persistent state and updates STATUS_BLOCK.
3.4 Critical Invariants
- Invariant A: STATUS_BLOCK fields are NEVER generated by LLM. They are direct reads of system metrics and state flags.
- Invariant B: Vault writes occur ONLY via the Audit Thread. No other process holds write locks.
- Invariant C: All gRPC traffic must present valid client certificates signed by the local Root CA.
4. Air-Gap Integration Protocols
4.1 Bundle Structure
The CAAA binaries will be embedded into the existing airgapped_llm tarball:

airgapped_llm_bundle/
├── binaries/
│   ├── caaa-core
│   ├── caaa-applet
│   ├── ollama (pre-bundled)
│   └── swi-prolog-runtime
├── models/
│   ├── tiny-llm.gguf
│   └── mistral-7b.gguf
├── config/
│   ├── caaa.toml
│   └── pki/ (pre-generated certs for initial boot)
└── systemd/
    ├── caaa-core.service
    └── caaa-applet.desktop

4.2 Installation Sequence
1\. Extract bundle to /opt/caaa.
2\. Run caaa-pki-init if no certs exist (generates Root CA + identities).
3\. Copy systemd units to /etc/systemd/system.
4\. Enable caaa-core.service.
5\. Add caaa-applet to COSMIC autostart configuration.
6\. Verify connectivity via caaa-cli status.
4.3 Offline Updates
Updates are performed via signed bundle replacement. The system verifies the GPG signature of the new bundle before allowing binary replacement. No over-the-air updates are permitted.
5. Risk Mitigation Frameworks
5.1 Technical Risks
- Risk: libcosmic instability during beta.
  - Mitigation: Implement a fallback GTK3 branch if libcosmic APIs break; isolate UI logic in a separate crate for easy swapping.
- Risk: Embedded Prolog/Lisp memory leaks.
  - Mitigation: Run reasoning engines in isolated subprocesses with strict memory limits (cgroups) rather than static linking if stability proves elusive.
- Risk: KVM/Kata Containers unavailable on target hardware.
  - Mitigation: Fallback to standard Linux namespaces/seccomp profiles for isolation; degrade security level but maintain functionality.
5.2 Accessibility Risks
- Risk: STATUS_BLOCK hallucination.
  - Mitigation: Enforced by architecture (Invariant A). Unit tests verify source of every field.
- Risk: Screen Reader incompatibility.
  - Mitigation: Early integration testing with Orca; strict adherence to GNOME accessibility APIs via libcosmic.
- Risk: Keyboard trap in popup.
  - Mitigation: Explicit focus management code ensuring Escape always closes popup and returns focus to previous window.
5.3 Security Risks
- Risk: Private Key exfiltration.
  - Mitigation: Keys stored with strict 0600 permissions; never logged; held in memory only after unlock.
- Risk: Prompt Injection bypassing Constitution.
  - Mitigation: Dual-model verification (small model checks large model output); Prolog rules are immutable at runtime.
