i## 5. Risk Mitigation Frameworks
;### 5.1 Technical Risks
- Risk: libcosmic instability during beta.
  - Mitigation: Implement a fallback GTK3 branch if libcosmic APIs break; isolate UI logic in a separate crate for easy swapping.
- Risk: Embedded Prolog/Lisp memory leaks.
  - Mitigation: Run reasoning engines in isolated subprocesses with strict memory limits (cgroups) rather than static linking if stability proves elusive.
- Risk: KVM/Kata Containers unavailable on target hardware.
  - Mitigation: Fallback to standard Linux namespaces/seccomp profiles for isolation; degrade security level but maintain functionality.
5.2 Accessibility Risks
- Risk: STATUS_BLOCK hallucination.
  - Mitigation: Enforced by architecture (Invariant A). Unit tests verify source of every field.
- Risk: Screen Reader incompatibility.
  - Mitigation: Early integration testing with Orca; strict adherence to GNOME accessibility APIs via libcosmic.
- Risk: Keyboard trap in popup.
  - Mitigation: Explicit focus management code ensuring Escape always closes popup and returns focus to previous window.
5.3 Security Risks
- Risk: Private Key exfiltration.
  - Mitigation: Keys stored with strict 0600 permissions; never logged; held in memory only after unlock.
- Risk: Prompt Injection bypassing Constitution.
  - Mitigation: Dual-model verification (small model checks large model output); Prolog rules are immutable at runtime.
